{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01VuSbv5325BM12Si7uvYcCb","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The error \"address lookup failed for otel-collector.otel.svc:4317: Domain name not found\" - this is a DNS resolution failure. The OTel exporter in the ingress-nginx controller is likely initialized once during reload, and the connection to the OTel collector is established via the original TOML with an empty host. The gRPC connection may be using the old TOML and needs a full restart of the nginx worker processes.\n\nBut wait - the OTel module in nginx might need a restart of nginx (not just a reload) to reinitialize the gRPC connection. Let me check if there's a way to force this.\nActually, looking at the logs more carefully, the TOML was regenerated with the correct host after the second ConfigMap update, but DNS is still failing to resolve `otel-collector.otel.svc:4317`. Since the controller runs in the `ingress-nginx` namespace and the collector is in `otel`, I need to verify whether the short DNS name works or if the full `otel-collector.otel.svc.cluster.local` is required. The issue might also be that the OTel collector pod itself isn't ready yet.\n\nLooking at the timestamps, the ConfigMap update happened at 14:11:22 and the TOML regenerated shortly after, but I deployed the collector afterward, so it may not have been running when the controller tried to connect. I'm also noticing there are no access log lines for the recent curl request in the controller logs—those would come from nginx itself, not the controller events.\n\nI remember seeing access log entries earlier with timestamps and curl user agents, but they're not showing up now even with the tail. The nginx module might need a full restart to reconnect to the new OTel collector endpoint since the last reload was before the collector pod started.\n\nThe gRPC exporter should reconnect automatically once DNS resolves, but the \"Domain name not found\" errors suggest the nginx worker processes might be caching the old NXDOMAIN response from before I created the otel namespace. Even if the export fails, the trace IDs should still populate in the access logs since they're generated locally by the nginx module, not from the collector. Let me check if the otel-check request actually has a corresponding access log entry with trace IDs. The access logs should appear in kubectl logs output, so let me send another request and check the logs immediately to see if the trace ID and span ID variables are actually being populated or if they're empty, which would indicate the OTel initialization failed.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1481,"cache_read_input_tokens":58131,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1481},"output_tokens":40,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"0969516e-3362-440b-9982-8ea728415013","uuid":"379447d2-bf78-434c-9da8-ed44225f7b95","request_id":"req_011Cc5BWnwgnriZiHvQMcSpi"}
